{
  "name": "pySLAM Probe (VLN-CE, pure policy)",
  "description": "A pure-policy VLN-CE navigator (CMA via policy_adapter_vlnce, NO LLM) with pySLAM observing the RGB-D stream. Cloned from vln/verified/straightforward.json; the only additions are four model_pyslam nodes: reset (fires once at episode start), track (per-step, consumes observe_loop's rgb+depth → SLAM pose), and get_trajectory / get_map after the loop (final_stop). The CMA policy drives navigation; pySLAM passively builds a map + trajectory alongside so we can see what the SLAM reconstructs from a policy-driven walk. Camera intrinsics are auto-aligned: env_habitat's observe emits an intrinsics port {fx,fy,cx,cy,width,height} wired into pyslam_reset, so the pinhole matches the real RGB sensor exactly; the track node resamples depth onto the RGB grid when the env renders them at different resolutions (CMA's RGB 224 vs depth 256). model_pyslam runs in local mode via the container bridge (docker agentcanvas/pyslam:cpu-fixed), so this graph runs end-to-end through the GraphExecutor. Two built-in geometry viewers make the SLAM visible: trajectoryViewer_slam draws the estimated camera path (blue) vs ground truth (grey) top-down, growing live per step from track's pose + observe_loop's gt pose (a pure in-loop sink); pointCloudViewer_slam renders the get_map point cloud — the sparse map — in a 3-D orbit view once the loop finishes (an after-loop band node). The map scatter is intentionally NOT wired into the trajectory view: get_map fires post-loop, and mixing an after-loop input with the live per-step poses would pull the trajectory node into the after-loop band (connectivity rule in graph_def.py).",
